1
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:22,760
Good evening.

2
00:00:22,861 --> 00:00:24,323
I hope you've had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:24,362 --> 00:00:28,088
I do not say happy, though I hope it has been happy.

4
00:00:29,070 --> 00:00:44,533
Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa

5
00:00:45,238 --> 00:00:54,033
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa.

6
00:00:54,052 --> 00:00:55,615
Homage to the blessed one.

7
00:00:56,616 --> 00:01:01,984
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

8
00:01:02,005 --> 00:01:11,280
I shall put on my special industry microphone here.

9
00:01:15,968 --> 00:01:16,388
Very good.

10
00:01:16,549 --> 00:01:18,689
I hope that makes me clear anyway.

11
00:01:18,911 --> 00:01:21,091
I hope you can hear me more clearly.

12
00:01:21,112 --> 00:01:24,995
So, I am going to labour the point.

13
00:01:25,596 --> 00:01:34,403
It's just to carry on with this not-self, because I remember my own personal confusion when I came across this teaching for the first time.

14
00:01:35,745 --> 00:01:44,472
It seemed to be saying that there was a not-self, which seemed very confusing, and the denial of a self.

15
00:01:44,875 --> 00:01:48,263
So the Buddha doesn't deny that there's a self, he just says it's unreal.

16
00:01:48,864 --> 00:01:51,049
And the not-self is a teaching tool.

17
00:01:51,069 --> 00:01:55,780
It's a way of saying, well, this is not me, it's not mine, and it's not myself.

18
00:01:56,063 --> 00:02:22,087
so the discourse i want to look at tonight is traditionally the second one he gave to his disciples uh to sorry to his five friends who had been his five friends uh during the pros during that time when he was um self-mortifying mainly through not eating and if you remember um he approaches them and of course they don't they don't respect him anymore he's gone soft

19
00:02:22,725 --> 00:02:28,159
But as he does approach, they see that something's changed.

20
00:02:28,180 --> 00:02:34,034
And when he begins to speak, he keeps asking them, have you ever heard me speak like this before?

21
00:02:34,150 --> 00:02:45,186
And just very slowly they open up to his teaching, and one of them actually becomes what we call a stream-enterer, just the first step of four steps that take us to liberation.

22
00:02:46,007 --> 00:02:49,070
So now, during the day, of course, they go off.

23
00:02:49,812 --> 00:02:58,104
Well, I would have thought it was some time, days maybe, because he does say that three of them went for alms round and came back, and they all left.

24
00:02:58,123 --> 00:03:00,106
Sometimes it was two of them went on alms round.

25
00:03:00,508 --> 00:03:07,599
but it's been sort of formalized into what's known as the Anattalakana Sutta, the discourse on not-self.

26
00:03:09,543 --> 00:03:12,627
So this, in a sense, encapsulates this whole teaching.

27
00:03:13,169 --> 00:03:17,115
So we'll just go through it and you'll see how it works.

28
00:03:17,414 --> 00:03:28,271
So again, he's at Benares in that deer park where he's met his five mendicants and he's talking to them and he says,

29
00:03:29,449 --> 00:03:30,651
is form.

30
00:03:30,731 --> 00:03:37,401
Now this word rupa is often translated as form, but obviously for us as human beings, it's basically the body.

31
00:03:38,782 --> 00:03:45,371
Everything has form, everything has some sort of spatial reality, a cupboard, a table.

32
00:03:46,171 --> 00:03:50,358
But as far as we're concerned, human beings, the rupa refers to this body.

33
00:03:52,199 --> 00:03:53,943
So he asks, is this body?

34
00:03:54,843 --> 00:03:57,347
This body is not self, he says to them.

35
00:03:57,546 --> 00:04:04,618
So the identity to the body is an illusion, is a delusion.

36
00:04:05,920 --> 00:04:12,512
And he says, well, if this body were you, you'd be able to have control over it.

37
00:04:12,912 --> 00:04:15,156
You'd be able to say, do not fall sick.

38
00:04:15,997 --> 00:04:18,261
Do not suffer from any affliction.

39
00:04:18,641 --> 00:04:21,867
You'd be able to tell it to grow a bit more, or I would anyway.

40
00:04:22,235 --> 00:04:24,017
and to have more hair on the head.

41
00:04:24,738 --> 00:04:29,867
It doesn't matter to me at this present time, but there was a time when I could have done with more hair on my head.

42
00:04:30,168 --> 00:04:34,194
But unfortunately, the center of control is elsewhere.

43
00:04:34,214 --> 00:04:36,298
So this is the important point.

44
00:04:36,377 --> 00:04:38,322
Where is the center of control?

45
00:04:39,202 --> 00:04:40,264
Where is the power?

46
00:04:41,247 --> 00:04:48,798
Who controls the body to stop it aging, to stop it dying, et cetera, et cetera, falling ill?

47
00:04:49,387 --> 00:04:54,815
Of course, we can move our arms around and shake our heads and all that sort of stuff, but it's very superficial.

48
00:04:56,620 --> 00:04:58,221
It's a bit like driving a car, isn't it?

49
00:04:58,302 --> 00:05:06,175
I mean, when you're in a car driving, you feel you're in control, but actually the car's propelling itself.

50
00:05:06,216 --> 00:05:10,163
It's got all sorts of stuff going on and anything can go wrong any time.

51
00:05:10,531 --> 00:05:18,023
And then when of course it breaks down or a tire bursts, then you realize you're not in control of the car.

52
00:05:18,062 --> 00:05:19,706
The control is quite superficial.

53
00:05:19,985 --> 00:05:21,608
So it's the same with the body.

54
00:05:24,153 --> 00:05:31,264
And when you realize that, you begin to realize that, how does he put it now?

55
00:05:32,245 --> 00:05:34,529
This body is not mine, right?

56
00:05:35,016 --> 00:05:37,180
You use it, but you don't actually own it.

57
00:05:38,062 --> 00:05:39,202
That's the distinction.

58
00:05:40,524 --> 00:05:45,252
Like with all objects, the ownership of an object is a legal fiction.

59
00:05:45,353 --> 00:05:46,574
I mean, we all agree to it.

60
00:05:46,675 --> 00:05:48,257
Like, for instance, this is my laptop.

61
00:05:49,177 --> 00:05:54,146
But that's just an agreement that we have between us as human beings.

62
00:05:55,047 --> 00:05:57,531
The fact is I don't actually own it.

63
00:05:58,067 --> 00:06:02,915
And of course, this ownership gets very big because then people own their houses.

64
00:06:03,454 --> 00:06:05,197
States own their country.

65
00:06:06,278 --> 00:06:10,404
And that causes all sorts of problems, this idea of possessing something.

66
00:06:11,887 --> 00:06:13,509
And then it's the body is not me.

67
00:06:14,050 --> 00:06:17,033
See, there's a disjunction.

68
00:06:17,074 --> 00:06:22,742
There's some sort of separation between me and the body because the body won't do what I tell it to do.

69
00:06:23,600 --> 00:06:25,262
And I am not the body.

70
00:06:25,322 --> 00:06:28,026
So this sense of self that I have is not the body.

71
00:06:28,326 --> 00:06:31,531
So again, we're going always back to identity.

72
00:06:31,571 --> 00:06:36,458
This was the big breakthrough of the Buddha, this problem of identity.

73
00:06:37,238 --> 00:06:46,232
If identity manifested as delusive action, it caused dukkha.

74
00:06:46,252 --> 00:06:53,201
So that's why the Four Noble Truths are phrased in what we can actually experience, unsatisfactoriness, suffering.

75
00:06:54,110 --> 00:06:57,274
But the root cause is this problem of identity.

76
00:07:00,858 --> 00:07:03,903
So then he goes on to talk about feeling.

77
00:07:04,283 --> 00:07:08,749
Now, feelings are both physical and emotional, heart feelings.

78
00:07:08,769 --> 00:07:19,843
So again, if you hurt your body, you bump your knee or something, or you bite your tongue, then at that moment, you're not in charge of the body.

79
00:07:19,863 --> 00:07:22,867
The body actually goes into a spasm of pain.

80
00:07:23,016 --> 00:07:25,824
And you can't say, well, you know, I don't want this pain.

81
00:07:25,863 --> 00:07:26,886
The pain remains.

82
00:07:26,906 --> 00:07:28,990
If you've got a headache, you have a headache.

83
00:07:29,632 --> 00:07:35,908
And you realize that when it comes to actually feelings in the body, again, very little control.

84
00:07:36,709 --> 00:07:41,480
You can take tablets these days, of course, but that's just covering over the pain.

85
00:07:43,132 --> 00:07:47,238
When it comes to emotions, if you feel sad, you feel sad.

86
00:07:47,298 --> 00:07:48,982
You can distract yourself.

87
00:07:49,002 --> 00:07:52,288
You can listen to some music or something or jump up and down and dance or whatever.

88
00:07:53,108 --> 00:07:55,132
But you can't get rid of the sadness that way.

89
00:07:55,153 --> 00:07:58,237
It's just buried underneath this attempt to escape it.

90
00:07:58,791 --> 00:08:04,119
And so you realize that we have very little power over our emotions.

91
00:08:04,158 --> 00:08:05,560
They arise and pass away.

92
00:08:06,302 --> 00:08:09,064
And this, of course, becomes obvious when you're sitting.

93
00:08:09,826 --> 00:08:20,940
You might sit with every intention, you know, to get deeply concentrated, have these wonderful insights, and all you have is these emotions coming up.

94
00:08:20,961 --> 00:08:27,389
You know, one minute there's all sorts of anxiety, there's all sorts of excitement, and then you're depressed, and then you're angry.

95
00:08:27,408 --> 00:08:28,089
It's just a...

96
00:08:28,372 --> 00:08:38,644
It's just a waterfall of uncontrolled emotions, uncontrollable emotions.

97
00:08:38,663 --> 00:08:40,605
And then we have perception.

98
00:08:40,625 --> 00:08:43,730
Now, perception belongs to the mind, that part which thinks.

99
00:08:43,850 --> 00:08:53,519
It thinks not only in an abstract sense of thoughts, words, but also in imagery, in imagination.

100
00:08:53,841 --> 00:08:55,883
So if I said the word cat,

101
00:08:55,863 --> 00:09:04,197
You not only understand what that means intellectually, you know, when it's got four legs and a little tail and all that, but also you have an image in your mind of what a cat is.

102
00:09:04,578 --> 00:09:06,722
So you know it's not a dog, right?

103
00:09:06,743 --> 00:09:09,326
We can normally tell clearly that this is a cat.

104
00:09:09,607 --> 00:09:11,390
It is not a dog, right?

105
00:09:11,370 --> 00:09:24,904
And these perceptions are not controlled by us, they arise because we see things, we hear things, we touch things, we smell things, we taste things, and then we make a photocopy of it.

106
00:09:25,326 --> 00:09:38,559
And the more we experience something that we see every day, a car for instance, it builds up a concept about it, an image which runs with the concept, concrete concept.

107
00:09:38,539 --> 00:09:53,206
so you know that this is a car it's not a truck it's not a train it's not a plane and then of course it gets very subtle because then we then it gets very um we say yes subtle becomes very big like freedom democracy

108
00:09:53,677 --> 00:09:56,879
But all these things are given to us.

109
00:09:57,721 --> 00:10:04,046
And they develop through our experience, through our cultures, and so on.

110
00:10:04,606 --> 00:10:05,648
And you can't get rid of it.

111
00:10:05,847 --> 00:10:10,231
You can't get rid of your sense of what your personal freedom means to you.

112
00:10:10,951 --> 00:10:12,994
You can change it, but you can't get rid of it.

113
00:10:13,634 --> 00:10:14,696
It's just there within you.

114
00:10:15,797 --> 00:10:22,822
It's the next part, the sankara, where we have some sort of choice, where we do have some sort of power.

115
00:10:24,169 --> 00:10:33,520
And all the time he's saying, well, these feelings, these perceptions, this body, you see, it's not right to say this is mine.

116
00:10:33,681 --> 00:10:34,662
You don't possess it.

117
00:10:34,741 --> 00:10:37,544
It changes of its own power.

118
00:10:37,625 --> 00:10:40,948
I was going to say free will, but there's no free will.

119
00:10:41,330 --> 00:10:43,572
It changes because of its own power.

120
00:10:44,092 --> 00:10:46,174
The eyes have a power to see.

121
00:10:46,995 --> 00:10:53,703
There's a process of vision which comes when the retina receives an object

122
00:10:53,683 --> 00:11:01,712
And you have this mentation going on, the whole process that's happening within the mind, within the brain mind.

123
00:11:02,374 --> 00:11:07,639
The brain would be the sensitive base for the mind.

124
00:11:10,583 --> 00:11:17,572
Now, when it comes to Sankara, which are the volitional conditionings, our habits, I much prefer just the word habits.

125
00:11:18,952 --> 00:11:20,455
You can't get rid of a habit.

126
00:11:20,514 --> 00:11:21,395
You can change it.

127
00:11:21,815 --> 00:11:25,419
You can draw it down so that it doesn't have any effect on you.

128
00:11:25,921 --> 00:11:32,490
But even in an arahat, old habits will arise, even those that belong to delusiveness.

129
00:11:33,471 --> 00:11:35,634
They'll arise, but they have no power.

130
00:11:36,336 --> 00:11:44,227
They're called vasana, they're called leftovers, traces, traces of past habits.

131
00:11:45,254 --> 00:11:58,115
The Buddha is said to have got rid of all of those, but that again is just hagiography, turning the Buddha into some magical being, some hyper human being, a beyond human being.

132
00:11:58,816 --> 00:12:00,639
But as a human being, he would have had habits.

133
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:06,469
That's what a human being is, is the body and a process of habituation.

134
00:12:08,389 --> 00:12:22,837
And again, when you see these habits come, when you find yourself in or acting out of a habit, you can become an observer of it, you can be aware of it and realize, well,

135
00:12:23,105 --> 00:12:25,107
I don't have to possess this.

136
00:12:25,168 --> 00:12:31,658
If I have an attitude of possessing it, it's going to be difficult for me to change it.

137
00:12:32,099 --> 00:12:36,767
If I identify with it, if I did that, it wouldn't be me.

138
00:12:36,807 --> 00:12:39,471
I remember an old aunt saying that.

139
00:12:39,671 --> 00:12:41,594
If she behaved like that, it wouldn't be me.

140
00:12:41,975 --> 00:12:44,719
So a very stuck idea of who I am.

141
00:12:44,778 --> 00:12:47,703
And that just produces staleness.

142
00:12:47,764 --> 00:12:49,145
It produces stagnancy.

143
00:12:49,649 --> 00:12:56,780
Whereas we want to be able to flow, to flow with events and to change with events.

144
00:12:57,962 --> 00:13:01,668
And that's how our lives grow, hopefully towards what is beneficial.

145
00:13:05,315 --> 00:13:09,822
By the way, I did see a little cartoon about going with the flow.

146
00:13:10,303 --> 00:13:13,128
It just said, only dead fish go with the flow.

147
00:13:13,688 --> 00:13:15,893
I don't think that's the meaning here.

148
00:13:17,442 --> 00:13:20,245
Then finally we have this consciousness.

149
00:13:21,666 --> 00:13:26,230
Now consciousness is the fifth of the khandhas.

150
00:13:26,331 --> 00:13:36,000
So remember the khandha, we've just been through them, the body, feelings, perceptions, habits and consciousness.

151
00:13:36,400 --> 00:13:42,386
Consciousness only arises when it is impinged upon, when something touches it.

152
00:13:42,754 --> 00:13:48,345
So it's like a screen, just like this screen that I'm looking at, like a monitor.

153
00:13:48,847 --> 00:13:50,436
There has to be an object.

154
00:13:50,888 --> 00:13:54,732
There has to be an object that impinges upon a sense base.

155
00:13:55,193 --> 00:13:58,238
So light must impinge upon the eye.

156
00:13:58,778 --> 00:14:00,662
A sound must impinge upon the ear.

157
00:14:01,062 --> 00:14:14,922
Something must come out of, for want of a better word, the subconscious, some sort of image, some sort of emotion, which arises and then touches upon this scheme, upon this screen of consciousness.

158
00:14:15,442 --> 00:14:24,202
Now, that screen of consciousness is not always there because it's being touched constantly by different impulses, by different stimuli.

159
00:14:24,672 --> 00:14:27,095
And you can't stop being conscious.

160
00:14:27,455 --> 00:14:28,836
I mean, you can put yourself asleep.

161
00:14:28,917 --> 00:14:31,980
I mean, obviously, when we go to sleep, we lose consciousness.

162
00:14:32,741 --> 00:14:35,365
Now you can hit yourself on the head and lose consciousness.

163
00:14:35,764 --> 00:14:40,029
But while we're awake, you cannot be not conscious, right?

164
00:14:40,049 --> 00:14:45,836
Your consciousness just arises because it's constantly being awoken by stimulus.

165
00:14:48,061 --> 00:15:15,434
so we don't have that control over consciousness whenever i put my eye on something i become aware of it i become it becomes part of my consciousness so again this idea of control you see and now if the center of control is elsewhere then it can't be me that's one of the definitions of i i me

166
00:15:15,618 --> 00:15:19,423
See, I know I'm not you because I can't control you.

167
00:15:20,304 --> 00:15:27,115
I know I'm not something outside me because I have limited control.

168
00:15:27,134 --> 00:15:35,427
I can move objects, I can control them, but they're still objects, they're still outside me, so I know it's not me.

169
00:15:35,948 --> 00:15:39,634
Now, when you're meditating, you're taking a position within yourself.

170
00:15:40,035 --> 00:15:43,278
of identifying with the observer, the feeler.

171
00:15:43,818 --> 00:15:49,364
Once you're in that position, everything's an object, and it's not under your control.

172
00:15:50,184 --> 00:15:58,111
The body offers feelings, sensations, the heart offers its moods and emotions, and the mind its thoughts and images.

173
00:15:58,511 --> 00:16:09,721
Whether you want it to or not, it isn't under your direct control when you're in the position of the observer, the feeler, the experiencer, the one who knows in vipassana.

174
00:16:14,477 --> 00:16:17,785
Somebody's actually translated Sankara as choices.

175
00:16:19,149 --> 00:16:21,596
There's a very good website called Sutta Central.

176
00:16:21,676 --> 00:16:23,640
That's just one word, Sutta Central.

177
00:16:24,482 --> 00:16:31,861
And there's another one, ancient Buddhist texts by Ananda Jyoti, who's an English monk, where he lives in Thailand, really.

178
00:16:32,095 --> 00:16:34,519
I've known him for a very long time.

179
00:16:34,818 --> 00:16:40,587
He also has a little website I just pointed out, Dharma Documentaries, they're really quite good.

180
00:16:42,530 --> 00:16:48,840
I'll post this up at some point.

181
00:16:48,860 --> 00:16:54,828
So now having explored the idea of control, the Buddha then goes on to impermanence.

182
00:16:55,484 --> 00:16:56,389
Ever-changing.

183
00:16:56,529 --> 00:16:58,299
What do you think, Mendicants?

184
00:16:58,321 --> 00:16:59,567
That's another word for Bikku, yeah?

185
00:17:00,130 --> 00:17:02,202
Is form permanent or impermanent?

186
00:17:02,486 --> 00:17:04,609
So is the body permanent or impermanent?

187
00:17:04,630 --> 00:17:07,815
So the answer is that it's impermanent, Venerable Sir.

188
00:17:08,236 --> 00:17:11,119
And if it's impermanent, is that suffering or happiness?

189
00:17:11,621 --> 00:17:20,032
Now, those two words, dukkha and sukha, you can translate as suffering or happiness, but I think it makes more sense to say, is that satisfying?

190
00:17:20,394 --> 00:17:21,414
Is it unsatisfying?

191
00:17:21,474 --> 00:17:26,722
Because one of the translations of dukkha is unsatisfactoriness.

192
00:17:26,887 --> 00:17:52,423
right and of course they say no sir it is unsatisfactory and if if it's impermanent unsatisfactory unsatisfactory and perishable is it fit to be regarded as this is mine i am this this is myself well the answer of course is no venerable so there's your basic questions yeah the basic question is

193
00:17:53,567 --> 00:18:17,195
is it permanent or impermanent right now all these things are permanent and impermanent if it's impermanent is that satisfying for you i mean if you arrive at a beautiful state of mind and then it disappears that's not very satisfactory you want to try and maintain it you want to try and develop it maybe and then he goes through the uh through the rest of it feeling so feelings are they permanent

194
00:18:17,564 --> 00:18:37,564
impermanent now this permanent impermanent is not it's not the same thing changing all the time they are completely new moments every consciousness is arising and passing away so it's it's it's at that fundamental level the impermanence is immediate and

195
00:18:37,544 --> 00:18:49,476
Even now consciousnesses are arising and passing away in me and in you at a speed such as that we're not aware of, so it gives some idea of continuity.

196
00:18:51,498 --> 00:18:56,182
But in Buddhist psychology these consciousnesses are flashing, they're flashing moment after moment.

197
00:18:58,523 --> 00:19:03,348
So then of course with perception, so perceptions arise and pass away just as quickly

198
00:19:03,835 --> 00:19:09,083
And is that desirable?

199
00:19:09,143 --> 00:19:10,144
Is that undesirable?

200
00:19:10,224 --> 00:19:11,948
Sometimes it is, sometimes it isn't.

201
00:19:13,830 --> 00:19:18,577
Then we have what he calls choices in this particular translation, sujata bhikkhu.

202
00:19:20,701 --> 00:19:24,207
But habits, I much prefer the word habits.

203
00:19:24,490 --> 00:19:25,951
Are they permanent, impermanent?

204
00:19:25,971 --> 00:19:27,113
They're constantly changing.

205
00:19:27,673 --> 00:19:30,695
They're either getting worse or getting better and so on.

206
00:19:31,237 --> 00:19:37,843
Consciousness is the very seat of impermanence because that's, as I say, flashing and rising and passing away.

207
00:19:38,242 --> 00:19:44,730
So none of this can be satisfactory to a sense of self because the sense of self wants to be in control.

208
00:19:45,109 --> 00:19:50,295
The identity, me, I want to be in control and I find myself not so.

209
00:19:53,599 --> 00:20:18,138
